text: It's annoying when they try to bring down-to-Earth drama into an event that, while monumentally significant, didn't have much drama at all. Almost everything went according to plan, Neil is a very ordinary and normal Midwestern dude, his family was fine... the actual landing was an incredible technological achievement, with plenty of highly technical/nerdy stuff to dramatize, but they wanna sell it to a wide audience, so they go with "your children may not have a father" etc. stuff which is cliched and uninteresting. So... I'm excited, but I suspect the film will be no more than 90 minutes and all the drama will be manufactured. A film like Apollo 13 -- the story itself had tons of drama, so all you had to do was tell it. With Apollo 11, all went perfectly, so... they gotta really reach to make it low-level dramatic for all the people who don't know what the landing actually entailed from an engineering point of view. Annoying. But I look forward to it.

text: Some thoughts on my mind: 1. At least two Oscar nominations for sure for Gosling and Chazelle. Hard to tell if also Best Movie. Maybe sound mixing, sound editing and some technical recognition. 2. Who cares if the story is accurate or not? I'm watching it because I'm a film lover, I like Gosling and Chazelle's work and this film surely looks worth watching. I bet the movie it's not about Apolo 11 or the landing per se but a personal and intimate look at a regular american citizen's life; a man called Neil Armstrong who just works hard on his job, which happens to be the first man on the moon. But seems to be a personal biopic. 3. I don't give a damn about the moon landing being a hoax directed by Stanley Kubrick, (if it is, kudos to Kubrick) but, let's allow others to believe and have some faith. Even if it's fake, to think that human race went to the Moon during the 60s is exciting, enjoyable and something really out of this world to believe in (pardon for the bad pun. Doesn't make it less true).

text: It looks to me like they took the glory aspects of "The Right Stuff" and turned it into a 2nd rate drama with a Ryan Reynolds stunt double. The movie does not look bad, but I dont feel it is something I am going out of my way to go see either. FYI, "Go for main engine start" was not the correct phrase for that era of space exploration.  In April of 1981 when the Space Shuttle program started was when they used "Go for main engine start". In 1969 they said "Ignition Sequence Start".  I know its a minor detail for some, but it tells me they were very loose with historical facts and details about the space programs history. I mean why not have Neal say when they landed on the moon "Houston, Tranquillity Base here. The Eagle made it." Instead of "The Eagle has landed". It just does not have the same ring to it.

text: I've watched this trailer a whole bunch. Not only does it bring out the feels in me, but I'm also hyped because this is a movie I've been wanting for years, all about NASA's mission to the moon. I remember my grandmother Mimi singing "I see the moon" to me when I was little. Hearing the song in this trailer brings out the feels, and brings back memories. Now I gotta go see this movie, and I'm taking my brother with me. Besides, being a man who works with computers and algorithms all day, I'm interested to see how some of the NASA personnel were able to work out math algorithms for the trajectories, and work with IBM computers to bring man to the moon, then giving those equations to Neil and the pilots so they can work them out. By the time I upgrade my computer in September 2020, I'll have a machine a few trillion times more powerful than the one it took to bring man to the moon. Even our phones are more powerful than that IBM computer. Those computers back then operated with punch cards, using Fortran as the language. It's great that they put that little detail in Hidden Figures.

text: Universal Pictures has released a brand new trailer for Damien Chazelle’s upcoming film, First Man. The film stars Ryan Gosling, Jason Clarke, Claire Foy, Kyle Chandler, Corey Stoll, Ciaran Hinds, Christopher Abbott, Patrick Fugit, and Lukas Haas.   On the heels of their six-time Academy Award®-winning smash, La La Land, Oscar®-winning director Damien Chazelle and star Ryan Gosling reteam for Universal Pictures’ First Man, the riveting story of NASA’s mission to land a man on the moon, focusing on Neil Armstrong and the years 1961-1969. A visceral, first-person account, based on the book by James R. Hansen, the movie will explore the sacrifices and the cost—on Armstrong and on the nation—of one of the most dangerous missions in history. text: ‪I like Ryan Gosling as an actor but he had nothing to do with this New World Order script that is a slap in the face of all Americans. ‬  ‪The producers, writers and financiers of this little flick decided ON PURPOSE (not a mistake or “oversight”) to not include the truly American iconic moment when Neal Armstrong and Buzz Aldrin planted our US Flag 🇺🇸 on the moon and then backed up to give it a nice and respectful salute. It was one of the very first things that they did. To put it in this little flick would have taken up maybe 15 seconds of screen time and used only one more prop: The Flag! ‬  ‪We beat the Commie Ruskies there, an important US goal that was first, and incredibly at the time, envisioned by John F. Kennedy in another iconic moment still in our collective memories as a People. Yes, it was important to us at the time that we did beat the Ruskies  - not to mention (and it definitely was not mentioned publically) that it was a very nice program to help develop very powerful rockets 🚀 for our defense at a time when the Ruskies were parking nukes 90 miles from our shore. ‬  ‪The producers, writers and financiers of this little flick are trying to claim that Neil Armstrong, being a shy man who shunned publicity, considered the accomplishment one of “the world’s” and not of just the little ‘ol US. They imply he would approve leaving out the planting of the Flag on the Moon. ‬  ‪Complete nonsense! He was a member of same Social Fraternity, Phi Delta Theta (mine, University of Miami FL; his Miami University OH) and I will stand up for his patriotism, which was well known. He loved his country. ‬  ‪The following is not the makings of a man lukewarm toward his country or about his also being the first AMERICAN to plant our US Flag 🇺🇸 on another heavenly body? No way!‬  ‪[Borrowed heavily from Wikipedia, which borrowed heavily from: Hansen, James R. (2005), First Man: The Life of Neil A. Armstrong.]‬  ‪He saw action in the Korean War where he was hit by anti-aircraft fire while making a low bombing run, and forced to bail out. ‬  ‪After flying such experimental aircraft as the X-15, he was chosen as NASA's first civilian astronaut to fly in space. During this mission Armstrong used some of his reentry control fuel to prevent a dangerous spin caused by a stuck thruster. His great skill and level head under life threatening circumstances saved his life and the Astronaut with him. That was #1. While training for his spaceflight as commander of Apollo 11, he had to eject from the Lunar Landing Research Vehicle moments before a fiery crash. That was #2. These things come in 3’s, right? On 20 July 1969, during the landing, at the very last possible moment - to avoid the disaster of crashing the LEM on top of a big boulder - Armstrong took over piloting from the auto-pilot and landed in a flat area beyond. And that was #3. Three times he almost died in service to his country. ‬  ‪His later years after leaving NASA were spent as a quiet college professor, although he did serve on a number of American companies Boards of Directors and was a spokesperson for other companies.  ‬  ‪He never acted as a spokesperson for any company that was not American.‬  ‪This was an American Man who loved his country, loved what it had allowed him to become and who loved and respected our American Flag 🇺🇸. Neil Armstrong is probably rolling over in his grave. Well, actually he was cremated and his remains scattered at sea aboard a US Ship of War and under a US Flag 🇺🇸. So maybe he’s rolling over on the waves that the producers, writers and financiers of this little flick intentionally omitted that the flag he planted on the Moon was an American Flag 🇺🇸.‬  ‪So, speaking for myself, I’ll wait until a good movie comes out about our national hero Neil A. Armstrong  - and maybe it will be one that respects our US Flag 🇺🇸 under which he proudly served.‬  ‪Carl D. Haggard, Sr.‬

text: Well, I was looking forward to this, but now I'll be boycotting it instead. I found out that this film is yet another victim of the Hollywood hate machine and its desire to rewrite and omit history. In this case THEY HAVE MADE SURE TO OMIT THE PLANTING OF THE AMERICAN FLAG ON THE MOON!   The Telegraph reports that Canadian actor Ryan Gosling said that the American moon landing “transcended countries and borders,” and that instead of being an American achievement, it was a “human achievement.” Globalist propaganda garbage. It was an American achievement which happened during the Cold War and succeeded in the iconic moment of planting the American flag on the moon, with America being the only country so far to this day to actually achieve manned landings there. It was a human achievement, in a race between the U.S. and the Soviet Union at the time. Trying to avoid portraying such a historical moment just comes off as more Hollywood smothering of anything involving American patriotism.  And the Moral Panic by the pearl clutchers of our time continues... Keep your PC safe spaces to yourselves.  B O Y C O T T

text: Neil's sons:  "We've read a number of comments about the film today and specifically about the absence of the flag planting scene, made largely by people who haven't seen the movie. As we've seen it multiple times, we thought maybe we should weigh in. This is a film that focuses on what you don't know about Neil Armstrong. It's a film that focuses on things you didn't see or may not remember about Neil's journey to the moon. The filmmakers spent years doing extensive research to get at the man behind the myth, to get at the story behind the story. It's a movie that gives you unique insight into the Armstrong family and fallen American Heroes like Elliot See and Ed White. It's a very personal movie about our dad's journey, seen through his eyes. This story is human and it is universal. Of course, it celebrates an America achievement. It also celebrates an achievement "for all mankind," as it says on the plaque Neil and Buzz left on the moon. It is a story about an ordinary man who makes profound sacrifices and suffers through intense loss in order to achieve the impossible. Although Neil didn't see himself that way, he was an American hero. He was also an engineer and a pilot, a father and a friend, a man who suffered privately through great tragedies with incredible grace. This is why, though there are numerous shots of the American flag on the moon, the filmmakers chose to focus on Neil looking back at the earth, his walk to Little West Crater, his unique, personal experience of completing this journey, a journey that has seen so many incredible highs and devastating lows. In short, we do not feel this movie is anti-American in the slightest. Quite the opposite. But don't take our word for it. We'd encourage everyone to go see this remarkable film and see for themselves."

Let me tell you again, the flag is in the movie!!! No, they don't "plant" the flag, but there is PLENTY OF SHOTS WITH THE FLAG ON THE MOON.  Armstrong and Aldrin spent 152 minutes walking on the moon, so a movie can't show every single minute of that. They did a number of task on the moon during their moonwalk, and it can't all fit into a single movie. I would rather see the astronauts exploring the moon and doing experiments, then see them planting a flag for five minutes. From a story telling perceptive, that would be a waste of screen time. The plaque they left behind read "Here men from the planet Earth first set foot upon the moon. July 1969 A.D. We came in peace FOR ALL MANKIND" Sound very unpatriotic to me, and more a celebration of human civilization. That is what this movie is trying to show. A celebration of the greatest technological achievement of OUR species.

text: You know; if a Canadian outfit wants to make a movie about the Apollo 11 mission, I have ZERO problems with that.  If they want to call it a human achievement, I have ZERO problems with that as well, because it WAS a great achievement for mankind.  However, when you intentionally leave out the second most iconic part of the whole mission (the planting of the flag) for the sole purpose of pushing your political agenda, I have a BIG problem with that.  It's a human achievement, but it isn't a human achievement AS OPPOSED TO an American achievement.  This was an AMERICAN achievement.  No other country helped.  America did it alone.  People point to the fact that there were some expatriated German scientists in NASA as somehow qualifying this is being an international achievement.

text: What a lot of people don't know about neil armstrong is his love of flight. It is an absolute in his life. He never lost that passion. His role as test pilot in the x-15 was more academic than throttle jockey. Spaceflight was just another aeronautical academic pursuit.  After he left NASA he taught aeronautical engineering at a small university. In his later years he was into sail planes and ultra-lights. He really liked gliders. He was a very interesting man and  was quite accomplished. He was a pianist as well.

It all directly follows from those original Canadians that worked on the Mercury, Gemini and Apollo programs.

author: ki ik

text: *One of the WORST movies I have seen regarding the Space Race.* It depicted Neil Armstrong as a very troubled depressed person who rarely knew how to handle anything in life without depression, withdrawing into a fantasy world and sadness. His home life was showed as a total failure with Armstrong too afraid to even talk to his kids before leaving for the Apollo 11 flight.  Armstrong is seen as lost, not knowing what to do with his life, very unfriendly, in his own little world and a person with a terrible bad attitude.  The scenes of the space crafts (especially the Gemini 8) are filmed as old rust buckets that are dirty, falling apart and poorly built. Case in point; many of the switches in the Gemini 8 cockpit were rusted, paint worn off surfaces, and sound effects for the Gemini 8 that sounded like a 100 year old tug boat about to fall apart.  A very poorly made ridiculous movie that seemed to be produced to belittle NASA and the U.S. Space Program as a broken down program run by idiots who hired an emotionally hurt and depressed test pilot, Neil Armstrong, for a mission that was carried out in piles of space junk.  The producers went out of their way to include scene after scene of Armstrong sitting in the dark, depressed, trying to figure life out, not having any clear goals in his life.  FOUR THUMBS DOWN! ...terrible movie!!

text: I don't know if you've read the book 'First Man: The life of Neil A. Armstrong' but, if you haven't, perhaps you should.  I have.  Several times.  It's a great book.   In the book the author goes into great detail  describing Armstrong's thoughts and concerns during the mission.   It was very apparent from Neil's words that two of his greatest concerns were the LM landing and the subsequent assent from the moon back into lunar orbit for it's docking with the command module.  Neither had ever been done before.  If the assent vehicle engine did not ignite, as Neil pointed out, Buzz and he would have only had a couple days before certain death.  The author also details Neil's concerns about the planting of flag.  The fact that the pole could only depressed it about 6" into the lunar soil before hitting the crust was of great concern.  Neil feared it would fall over and lay forever in the lunar dust.  He seemed very relieved when they managed to get the flag to stay upright.  It was obviously very important to him.   It was clear the assent back into lunar orbit was very tense requiring all of their attention focused inside of the vehicle to avoid any mistakes that could have cost them their lives.  As Neil points out, that once the engine ignited he did not much time to look out the window at the surface of the moon.  But Neil did make time for one thing as they rocketed away:  to check on the flag.  He was saddened to see that their rocket burn on lift off had blown the flag over and it was laying in the dust.  I can't say if the movie 'First Man' dishonored the flag or not since I have not bothered to watch it.  Nor do I plan to.  I can only surmise two things:  One, that the flag was unimportant to those who created the movie.  And two, from Neil's own words, that this particular flag was very important to him.
